# Thyroid Gland

> The thyroid gland is the **largest purely endocrine gland** (~25 g), lying in the anterior neck at C5–T1. It secretes **thyroxine (T4)** and **triiodothyronine (T3)** to regulate basal metabolic rate, and **calcitonin** to lower serum calcium.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Endocrine System]]
- Controlled by: [[Pituitary Gland]] TSH → [[Hypothalamus]] TRH
- Location: Anterior to [[Trachea]] (C5–T1 level); overlaps [[Larynx]] (cricoid level)
- Posterior relations: Parathyroid glands on posterior surface; [[Parathyroid Glands]]
- Medial: [[Trachea]], [[Esophagus]]
- Blood supply: **Superior thyroid artery** (1st branch of external carotid); **Inferior thyroid artery** (from thyrocervical trunk of subclavian); occasionally thyroidea ima (from arch of aorta)
- Venous drainage: Superior + middle thyroid veins → IJV; Inferior thyroid veins → brachiocephalic veins
- Lymphatics: Prelaryngeal, pretracheal, paratracheal, cervical nodes
- Innervation: Sympathetic (superior + middle cervical ganglia); parasympathetic (vagus/recurrent laryngeal)
- Key relation: **Recurrent laryngeal nerve (RLN)** passes in tracheo-oesophageal groove — at risk in thyroid surgery

## 🔬 Structure

| Part | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Right lobe | Larger; ~5 cm × 3 cm |
| Left lobe | Slightly smaller |
| **Isthmus** | Bridge across trachea at rings 2–4; overlies in thyroidectomy approach |
| Pyramidal lobe | Present in 50%; remnant of thyroglossal duct; ascends from isthmus |
| Fibrous capsule | Sends septa dividing gland into lobules |
| Berry's ligament | Posterior condensation; anchors thyroid to trachea; close to RLN |

**Follicles** — spherical units; follicular cells (thyrocytes) produce T3/T4 and secrete into colloid (thyroglobulin); parafollicular C cells (calcitonin)

## ⚙️ Thyroid Hormones
- **T4 (thyroxine)** — pro-hormone; converted peripherally to **T3** (active) by deiodinase
- T3/T4: ↑ BMR, ↑ HR, ↑ O₂ consumption, ↑ protein synthesis, essential for growth + brain development
- **Calcitonin** — from C cells; ↓ osteoclast activity → ↓ Ca²⁺ (clinical role minor in adults)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
| Condition | Key Points |
|-----------|-----------|
| **Hypothyroidism** | ↑TSH, ↓FT4; fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, bradycardia; Rx: levothyroxine |
| **Hyperthyroidism** | ↓TSH, ↑FT4; Graves' (TSH-R Ab, exophthalmos), toxic multinodular goitre, thyroiditis |
| **Thyroid cancer** | Papillary (most common, RET/PTC, good prognosis), follicular, medullary (calcitonin, MEN2), anaplastic (worst) |
| **Thyroid nodule** | FNAC for assessment; ultrasound Bethesda criteria |
| **Thyroid surgery risk** | RLN injury → hoarseness; bilateral → stridor, airway emergency; hypoparathyroidism → hypocalcaemia |
| **Thyroid storm** | Life-threatening hyperthyroidism; fever, tachycardia, AF, confusion; Rx: PTU, β-blockers, steroids |

